Week 9:
In your own words, explain what inheritance is and why it's
useful. Imagine you're talking to someone who has no
background in programming like a friend or family member.
You can use simple, everyday examples to help make your
explanation clear.


*Inheritance is the process of data and information being passed down 
*from a parent class or object to its child. It’s the concept that if 
*there is data associated with an item, and that item is duplicated, 
*the data associated with the original will also be attached to the new 
*item. In C++, the inherited data is dependent on the public and private
* members of the class. For example, if I has a giant wheel of cheese, 
*and I took a large chunk from it, it would still have the original 
*qualities of the full cheese, but I could use the smaller piece to add 
*it to a recipe, altering the smaller piece of the original cheese. Perhaps
* a better example is if I have a picture that has a bunch of metadata 
*attached to it, and I wanted to copy the file completely, the new copy 
*would have the metadata from the original image, such as location, time 
*taken, and device used.
